WEBVTT

1
00:00:05.020 --> 00:00:11.600
Hi everyone, I'm Sam from the Free Wings flight school and today we'll work through the topic of flight practice together.

2
00:00:12.760 --> 00:00:17.360
Flight practice — and we're sitting here in a studio, which doesn't quite fit together.

3
00:00:18.660 --> 00:00:25.860
What we want to do first is acquire knowledge, and that's something we have to, or can, do well in the theory part.

4
00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:33.140
Because when we have the knowledge, we can go out and train, and once we've trained, we can move on to the area of skill.

5
00:00:33.140 --> 00:00:40.520
And only this path works: acquiring knowledge, training, and then moving into skill.

6
00:00:40.640 --> 00:00:43.480
If you skip one of these, it usually doesn't go well.

7
00:00:43.800 --> 00:00:48.560
So we're concentrating here on acquiring the knowledge of flight practice.

8
00:00:49.240 --> 00:00:56.630
The goal of this course is ultimately that you pass the flight-practice theme of the SHV theory exam without trouble,

9
00:00:56.630 --> 00:01:00.690
ideally with full marks.

10
00:01:01.090 --> 00:01:03.630
Of course best with 100 points, i.e. 100%.

11
00:01:03.890 --> 00:01:06.480
That's the right approach at the end.

12
00:01:06.480 --> 00:01:12.530
For all of this, as practice also says, it's helpful to imagine the whole thing like a flight.

13
00:01:12.530 --> 00:01:17.490
Meaning, we actually start flying at home.

14
00:01:17.490 --> 00:01:20.760
Flying is something you have to prepare.

15
00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:27.760
It's usually not great to simply go straight to the launch site without any prior preparation

16
00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:29.760
and then be surprised by what you encounter.

17
00:01:29.760 --> 00:01:33.760
If you think at home about what you actually want to do today,

18
00:01:33.760 --> 00:01:35.760
that can make things much easier.

19
00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:41.760
And that includes the very first thing — namely, whether you're even fit to fly.

20
00:01:41.760 --> 00:01:45.780
That means: do I actually know what my condition is?

21
00:01:45.780 --> 00:01:47.780
Am I clear-headed?

22
00:01:47.780 --> 00:01:51.780
Have I not had any rough nights and am still half hung over?

23
00:01:51.780 --> 00:01:52.780
Am I fit?

24
00:01:52.780 --> 00:01:58.780
Have I taken any medication that, if I have some kind of pain, might mask it?

25
00:01:58.780 --> 00:02:04.110
Those are all things that can affect us heavily and may make flying unwise.

26
00:02:04.110 --> 00:02:11.110
And also important that we gather information about the weather and the things that affect us.

27
00:02:11.110 --> 00:02:15.110
There's a very simple rule for this, the so-called FFG rule.

28
00:02:15.110 --> 00:02:17.110
That's now in relation to the weather.

29
00:02:17.110 --> 00:02:21.110
If we keep this in mind — currently in the Corona era,

30
00:02:21.110 --> 00:02:24.110
the FFP2 mask is missing as a word.

31
00:02:24.110 --> 00:02:27.160
As a memory aid, we have the FFG rule.

32
00:02:27.160 --> 00:02:31.160
And the FFG rule is nothing other than: do we expect a hazard

33
00:02:31.160 --> 00:02:32.160
called foehn?

34
00:02:32.160 --> 00:02:33.160
Do we expect a hazard

35
00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:35.160
called front?

36
00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:36.160
And do we expect a hazard

37
00:02:36.160 --> 00:02:38.160
called thunderstorm?

38
00:02:38.160 --> 00:02:41.160
If one of these three appears in the weather report,

39
00:02:41.160 --> 00:02:44.750
our ears need to grow very big

40
00:02:44.750 --> 00:02:46.750
and we need to hear what's going on.

41
00:02:46.750 --> 00:02:52.750
Because, as you know — a front, which also comes up in detail in the meteo part of this course,

42
00:02:52.750 --> 00:02:54.750
usually brings a lot of wind with it.

43
00:02:54.750 --> 00:02:58.750
Strong wind is always rather bad for paragliding,

44
00:02:58.750 --> 00:03:00.750
because we travel relatively slowly.

45
00:03:00.750 --> 00:03:04.500
Foehn is generally a dangerous situation.

46
00:03:04.500 --> 00:03:06.500
As a student you don't belong in the air.

47
00:03:06.500 --> 00:03:08.520
Later, when you're very experienced,

48
00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:10.890
there are geographic locations

49
00:03:10.890 --> 00:03:13.890
that can allow flying even in foehn.

50
00:03:13.890 --> 00:03:15.890
But that takes a lot of prior knowledge.

51
00:03:15.890 --> 00:03:18.890
And thunderstorms — also very unpredictable.

52
00:03:18.890 --> 00:03:20.890
You have to have lots of experience.

53
00:03:20.890 --> 00:03:22.890
And in general with thunderstorms, it's better to

54
00:03:22.890 --> 00:03:24.890
land freely and safely

55
00:03:24.890 --> 00:03:26.890
than to try to squeeze out some flight,

56
00:03:26.890 --> 00:03:28.890
which usually doesn't end well.

57
00:03:28.890 --> 00:03:36.100
Then it's important to recognise the requirements.

58
00:03:36.100 --> 00:03:39.220
Also regarding rules and regulations.

59
00:03:39.220 --> 00:03:41.220
Of course there's a glider chart

60
00:03:41.220 --> 00:03:44.220
that describes the legal situation.

61
00:03:44.220 --> 00:03:46.220
And there are also airspace restrictions

62
00:03:46.220 --> 00:03:49.220
that can be quite severe if you don't know about them.

63
00:03:49.220 --> 00:03:52.220
And to find out about these airspace restrictions,

64
00:03:52.220 --> 00:03:57.300
you have to check the DABS for each flight day,

65
00:03:57.300 --> 00:04:00.300
to see whether a current airspace restriction is in effect.

66
00:04:00.300 --> 00:04:02.300
It can be something big,

67
00:04:02.300 --> 00:04:05.300
such as the World Economic Forum in Davos,

68
00:04:05.300 --> 00:04:08.300
where the airspace is closed over a very wide area.

69
00:04:08.300 --> 00:04:10.300
And I can imagine

70
00:04:10.300 --> 00:04:12.300
that there too, if you tried to fly in,

71
00:04:12.300 --> 00:04:14.300
you'd very quickly get an escort

72
00:04:14.300 --> 00:04:16.300
from somewhat larger aircraft,

73
00:04:16.300 --> 00:04:17.300
since a paraglider

74
00:04:17.300 --> 00:04:19.300
would be rather unwise to fly into that.

75
00:04:19.300 --> 00:04:21.300
There are also small restrictions,

76
00:04:21.300 --> 00:04:23.300
for example, if there's a vote,

77
00:04:23.300 --> 00:04:24.300
the country has a referendum,

78
00:04:24.300 --> 00:04:26.300
the country-square is full of people,

79
00:04:26.300 --> 00:04:28.300
there's a cylinder above it

80
00:04:28.300 --> 00:04:29.300
where it's also forbidden

81
00:04:29.300 --> 00:04:30.300
to fly over it,

82
00:04:30.300 --> 00:04:33.300
simply because there's a very large gathering of people.

83
00:04:33.300 --> 00:04:34.300
You'll find this information on the DABS,

84
00:04:34.300 --> 00:04:36.300
described relatively well.

85
00:04:36.300 --> 00:04:39.300
And of course you also have to pay attention

86
00:04:39.300 --> 00:04:41.380
to where you want to fly,

87
00:04:41.380 --> 00:04:42.380
for example on a cross-country flight,

88
00:04:42.380 --> 00:04:44.380
and those are military flights,

89
00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:46.380
military operating hours — important

90
00:04:46.380 --> 00:04:48.380
that you know them,

91
00:04:48.380 --> 00:04:52.110
because depending on the time you can fly higher

92
00:04:52.110 --> 00:04:55.160
than when the military is active.

93
00:04:55.160 --> 00:04:57.160
On the weekend it's a bit less restrictive

94
00:04:57.160 --> 00:04:59.160
than during the week, for example.

95
00:04:59.160 --> 00:05:01.460
What also belongs to this is

96
00:05:01.460 --> 00:05:03.460
checking the equipment,

97
00:05:03.460 --> 00:05:04.460
knowing

98
00:05:04.460 --> 00:05:07.460
that the gear you have with you works.

99
00:05:07.460 --> 00:05:10.460
That includes, for example, charging the batteries.

100
00:05:10.460 --> 00:05:12.460
It's no use if you end up in an emergency situation

101
00:05:12.460 --> 00:05:14.460
and your phone battery is empty,

102
00:05:14.460 --> 00:05:18.700
then you can't tell anyone where you are.

103
00:05:18.700 --> 00:05:21.700
And also the gear in general,

104
00:05:21.700 --> 00:05:23.700
the condition of the wing,

105
00:05:23.700 --> 00:05:24.700
that it's okay,

106
00:05:24.700 --> 00:05:27.700
if you've had a long flying break,

107
00:05:27.700 --> 00:05:28.700
but also being sure

108
00:05:28.700 --> 00:05:30.700
that the reserve parachute is freshly packed.

109
00:05:30.700 --> 00:05:33.700
You should have it repacked at least once a year.

110
00:05:33.700 --> 00:05:36.700
By someone who really knows how to do it.

111
00:05:36.700 --> 00:05:39.850
And the wing itself, knowing

112
00:05:39.850 --> 00:05:41.850
that the condition you stored it in

113
00:05:41.850 --> 00:05:43.850
comes back out the same way.

114
00:05:43.850 --> 00:05:45.850
Meaning, it wouldn't be smart

115
00:05:45.850 --> 00:05:47.850
to pack up the wing

116
00:05:47.850 --> 00:05:49.850
if it just landed in muck

117
00:05:49.850 --> 00:05:51.850
and the muck is on the wing

118
00:05:51.850 --> 00:05:53.850
and the wing then spends weeks in the car boot,

119
00:05:53.850 --> 00:05:55.850
where it's warm.

120
00:05:55.850 --> 00:05:57.850
Those are all things

121
00:05:57.850 --> 00:05:59.850
that will come up later in the equipment course,

122
00:05:59.850 --> 00:06:01.850
that aren't good for the wing.

123
00:06:01.850 --> 00:06:03.850
And of course it can also happen

124
00:06:03.850 --> 00:06:06.220
that accordingly, what you expect

125
00:06:06.220 --> 00:06:07.580
isn't what you find.

126
00:06:07.580 --> 00:06:08.580
Also important

127
00:06:08.580 --> 00:06:10.580
is bringing provisions,

128
00:06:10.580 --> 00:06:12.580
having enough to drink with you.

129
00:06:12.580 --> 00:06:14.820
Drinking is actually the most important thing.

130
00:06:14.820 --> 00:06:16.820
Food is usually such

131
00:06:16.820 --> 00:06:18.820
that you can get energy quickly

132
00:06:18.820 --> 00:06:20.820
from energy bars.

133
00:06:20.820 --> 00:06:21.820
Drinking is often forgotten

134
00:06:21.820 --> 00:06:23.820
and sometimes also deliberately not done,

135
00:06:23.820 --> 00:06:25.820
because it has a small drawback

136
00:06:25.820 --> 00:06:26.820
when you drink a lot.

137
00:06:26.820 --> 00:06:27.820
You also have to go to the toilet.

138
00:06:27.820 --> 00:06:29.820
But there are solutions for that too,

139
00:06:29.820 --> 00:06:31.820
such as urinal condoms,

140
00:06:31.820 --> 00:06:33.820
where you can even pee in the air.

141
00:06:33.820 --> 00:06:35.840
And for women there are also nappies,

142
00:06:35.840 --> 00:06:38.860
so this problem can be solved.

143
00:06:38.860 --> 00:06:40.860
But it's not smart

144
00:06:40.860 --> 00:06:43.860
to skip drinking because of this issue.

145
00:06:43.860 --> 00:06:44.860
Drinking is very important

146
00:06:44.860 --> 00:06:46.860
so we stay sharp,

147
00:06:46.860 --> 00:06:48.860
stay fit in the air,

148
00:06:48.860 --> 00:06:50.860
and so the end of the flying day

149
00:06:50.860 --> 00:06:52.860
isn't ruined by a headache

150
00:06:52.860 --> 00:06:53.860
that we'd have

151
00:06:53.860 --> 00:06:57.660
if we drank too little.

152
00:06:57.660 --> 00:06:59.660
Then, once we've done all the preparation

153
00:06:59.660 --> 00:07:01.660
at home,

154
00:07:01.660 --> 00:07:02.660
it makes sense

155
00:07:02.660 --> 00:07:05.660
to look at the landing site first.

156
00:07:05.660 --> 00:07:07.660
Because at the landing site especially

157
00:07:07.660 --> 00:07:10.420
dangers are obvious,

158
00:07:10.420 --> 00:07:12.420
because you have relatively little altitude

159
00:07:12.420 --> 00:07:14.420
as you approach it.

160
00:07:14.420 --> 00:07:15.420
And it's good

161
00:07:15.420 --> 00:07:17.420
to already know it.

162
00:07:17.420 --> 00:07:19.420
That means a proper landing-site inspection

163
00:07:19.420 --> 00:07:21.420
absolutely makes sense.

164
00:07:21.420 --> 00:07:22.420
We already check

165
00:07:22.420 --> 00:07:24.420
where there are possible obstacles,

166
00:07:24.420 --> 00:07:26.420
for instance cables

167
00:07:26.420 --> 00:07:27.460
that are nearby,

168
00:07:27.460 --> 00:07:29.460
running across the valley.

169
00:07:29.460 --> 00:07:31.460
Where there's a big tree, for example,

170
00:07:31.460 --> 00:07:32.460
that you might have to take into account

171
00:07:32.460 --> 00:07:34.460
when planning your landing pattern.

172
00:07:34.460 --> 00:07:36.460
And in general how the landing pattern

173
00:07:36.460 --> 00:07:37.460
is set on this terrain.

174
00:07:37.460 --> 00:07:39.460
There are good aids for this,

175
00:07:39.460 --> 00:07:41.460
namely usually the local pilots,

176
00:07:41.460 --> 00:07:43.460
who know how the landing pattern

177
00:07:43.460 --> 00:07:45.460
is set up in their area.

178
00:07:45.460 --> 00:07:47.460
The standard pattern is a left-hand pattern.

179
00:07:47.460 --> 00:07:49.460
But that can vary depending on the conditions

180
00:07:49.460 --> 00:07:51.460
at the landing site

181
00:07:51.460 --> 00:07:53.460
and may be a right-hand pattern instead,

182
00:07:53.460 --> 00:07:54.460
depending on the wind.

183
00:07:54.460 --> 00:07:56.460
It's usually well marked

184
00:07:56.460 --> 00:07:58.460
at the landing site, visible on a sign.

185
00:07:58.460 --> 00:08:00.460
If not, ask the locals.

186
00:08:00.460 --> 00:08:01.830
Also important

187
00:08:01.830 --> 00:08:02.830
is that we know

188
00:08:02.830 --> 00:08:05.260
where we're actually flying through.

189
00:08:05.260 --> 00:08:07.260
We do a bit of flight planning.

190
00:08:07.260 --> 00:08:08.260
Meaning, when we're at the landing site,

191
00:08:08.260 --> 00:08:09.260
we can already check

192
00:08:09.260 --> 00:08:10.260
where the launch site is.

193
00:08:10.260 --> 00:08:11.260
Usually you can see

194
00:08:11.260 --> 00:08:14.260
where a possible emergency landing site might be.

195
00:08:14.260 --> 00:08:16.260
If a landing site were closed,

196
00:08:16.260 --> 00:08:17.260
which can happen,

197
00:08:17.260 --> 00:08:18.260
say something has occurred,

198
00:08:18.260 --> 00:08:19.260
they have to pick up a hiker

199
00:08:19.260 --> 00:08:20.260
who has broken a leg.

200
00:08:20.260 --> 00:08:23.260
The Rega helicopter lands right on the landing site.

201
00:08:23.260 --> 00:08:24.260
It's important

202
00:08:24.260 --> 00:08:25.260
that we then know

203
00:08:25.260 --> 00:08:26.260
where we'll land instead.

204
00:08:26.260 --> 00:08:28.700
And there are things we have to think about

205
00:08:28.700 --> 00:08:29.700
that we should consider

206
00:08:29.700 --> 00:08:31.700
regarding turbulence.

207
00:08:31.700 --> 00:08:32.700
There are houses,

208
00:08:32.700 --> 00:08:33.700
big trees

209
00:08:33.700 --> 00:08:35.700
that could create turbulence.

210
00:08:35.700 --> 00:08:37.700
A bit of valley wind

211
00:08:37.700 --> 00:08:39.700
that could disturb us during landing.

212
00:08:39.700 --> 00:08:42.700
Making all these considerations in advance

213
00:08:42.700 --> 00:08:45.700
really makes the flight much easier overall,

214
00:08:45.700 --> 00:08:48.700
because you then have a plan B in mind.

215
00:08:48.700 --> 00:08:50.700
And plan B is something very important.

216
00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:52.700
We should never fly somewhere

217
00:08:52.700 --> 00:08:53.700
if we don't know

218
00:08:53.700 --> 00:08:54.700
what we'll do

219
00:08:54.700 --> 00:08:55.700
if it doesn't go

220
00:08:55.700 --> 00:08:56.700
the way we expected.

221
00:08:56.700 --> 00:08:58.710
Always think in advance,

222
00:08:58.710 --> 00:08:59.710
what to do when.

223
00:08:59.710 --> 00:09:02.850
That also includes the consideration

224
00:09:02.850 --> 00:09:04.850
regarding wildlife.

225
00:09:04.850 --> 00:09:07.850
We have wildlife protection as a major topic.

226
00:09:07.850 --> 00:09:09.850
It used to always be a secondary concern.

227
00:09:09.850 --> 00:09:10.850
People used to say

228
00:09:10.850 --> 00:09:12.850
that paragliders

229
00:09:12.850 --> 00:09:14.850
hardly disturb wildlife.

230
00:09:14.850 --> 00:09:15.850
The new study

231
00:09:15.850 --> 00:09:16.850
that just came out

232
00:09:16.850 --> 00:09:17.850
shows rather the opposite,

233
00:09:17.850 --> 00:09:19.850
that the paraglider pilot

234
00:09:19.850 --> 00:09:21.850
does have a bit of responsibility

235
00:09:21.850 --> 00:09:22.850
toward wildlife.

236
00:09:22.850 --> 00:09:23.850
And it's also very important

237
00:09:23.850 --> 00:09:24.850
to keep that in mind.

238
00:09:24.850 --> 00:09:25.850
On the one hand we have

239
00:09:25.850 --> 00:09:27.850
the local wildlife agreements,

240
00:09:27.850 --> 00:09:29.850
which are also on the info board,

241
00:09:29.850 --> 00:09:31.850
usually described near the lift,

242
00:09:31.850 --> 00:09:32.850
where, for instance, there are zones

243
00:09:32.850 --> 00:09:34.850
you should not fly into at all.

244
00:09:34.850 --> 00:09:36.180
But it's also important

245
00:09:36.180 --> 00:09:38.180
to know a bit

246
00:09:38.180 --> 00:09:40.180
about wildlife in general.

247
00:09:40.180 --> 00:09:41.180
And in the theory questions

248
00:09:41.180 --> 00:09:43.180
we know for this topic,

249
00:09:43.180 --> 00:09:44.180
there are also lots of questions

250
00:09:44.180 --> 00:09:46.180
about wildlife protection.

251
00:09:46.180 --> 00:09:48.180
Here, for example, it's about

252
00:09:48.180 --> 00:09:51.360
when our animals in the Alps

253
00:09:51.360 --> 00:09:52.360
have their young,

254
00:09:52.360 --> 00:09:53.360
because that's exactly the time

255
00:09:53.360 --> 00:09:55.360
of spring.

256
00:09:55.360 --> 00:09:56.360
And in spring

257
00:09:56.360 --> 00:09:59.360
we fly beautifully high.

258
00:09:59.360 --> 00:10:00.360
That means

259
00:10:00.360 --> 00:10:01.360
we also reach those places

260
00:10:01.360 --> 00:10:03.360
where, for example, the eagles,

261
00:10:03.360 --> 00:10:05.360
the chamois and the ibex

262
00:10:05.360 --> 00:10:07.360
raise their young.

263
00:10:07.360 --> 00:10:09.360
With eagles, you really have to

264
00:10:09.360 --> 00:10:11.360
expect, from March to May,

265
00:10:11.360 --> 00:10:13.360
that they're sitting on the eyrie

266
00:10:13.360 --> 00:10:16.360
and also defending their territory.

267
00:10:16.360 --> 00:10:18.360
With chamois it's in May,

268
00:10:18.360 --> 00:10:21.470
and with ibex it's in June.

269
00:10:21.470 --> 00:10:22.470
And in this time,

270
00:10:22.470 --> 00:10:23.470
if you see animals,

271
00:10:23.470 --> 00:10:25.620
fly away from them.

272
00:10:25.620 --> 00:10:27.620
It's simply fair to the animal

273
00:10:27.620 --> 00:10:29.620
not to tell yourself something like:

274
00:10:29.620 --> 00:10:30.620
the thermal here

275
00:10:30.620 --> 00:10:31.620
is especially good,

276
00:10:31.620 --> 00:10:32.620
I don't care

277
00:10:32.620 --> 00:10:33.620
if there are chamois below me —

278
00:10:33.620 --> 00:10:34.620
instead, fly away.

279
00:10:34.620 --> 00:10:36.620
The animals already have enough stress

280
00:10:36.620 --> 00:10:38.620
from all kinds of environmental pressures,

281
00:10:38.620 --> 00:10:40.620
so we, as paraglider pilots,

282
00:10:40.620 --> 00:10:41.620
who are so close to nature,

283
00:10:41.620 --> 00:10:43.620
shouldn't cause additional stress.

284
00:10:43.620 --> 00:10:45.720
As I said,

285
00:10:45.720 --> 00:10:47.720
the local conditions

286
00:10:47.720 --> 00:10:48.720
for individual wildlife protection areas

287
00:10:48.720 --> 00:10:50.720
are usually clearly displayed

288
00:10:50.720 --> 00:10:54.330
at the lift stations.

289
00:10:54.330 --> 00:10:56.340
And otherwise, don't be shy here either,

290
00:10:56.340 --> 00:10:58.340
ask the locals.

291
00:10:58.340 --> 00:11:01.340
Everyone is always happy to give information.

292
00:11:01.340 --> 00:11:06.370
When we get to the mountain,

293
00:11:06.370 --> 00:11:07.370
heading toward the launch site,

294
00:11:07.370 --> 00:11:09.900
for many it may be the case

295
00:11:09.900 --> 00:11:12.900
that they already feel a little nervous.

296
00:11:12.900 --> 00:11:15.100
But nervousness is ultimately

297
00:11:15.100 --> 00:11:16.100
a good thing,

298
00:11:16.100 --> 00:11:19.100
because it makes you look at things carefully.

299
00:11:19.100 --> 00:11:20.100
And especially

300
00:11:20.100 --> 00:11:23.100
if you don't know a launch site,

301
00:11:23.100 --> 00:11:25.100
for example doing a hike & fly,

302
00:11:25.100 --> 00:11:26.100
arriving at a terrain

303
00:11:26.100 --> 00:11:28.100
you don't know at all,

304
00:11:28.100 --> 00:11:29.100
it's all the more important

305
00:11:29.100 --> 00:11:30.100
that the guiding principle

306
00:11:30.100 --> 00:11:31.100
written here

307
00:11:31.100 --> 00:11:32.100
is observed.

308
00:11:32.100 --> 00:11:33.100
Namely:

309
00:11:33.100 --> 00:11:34.100
from every launch site

310
00:11:34.100 --> 00:11:35.100
it must

311
00:11:35.100 --> 00:11:37.100
be possible at any time, safely,

312
00:11:37.100 --> 00:11:39.100
to abort the launch.

313
00:11:39.100 --> 00:11:42.540
If we launch from a cliff

314
00:11:42.540 --> 00:11:44.540
where we have only a short run,

315
00:11:44.540 --> 00:11:46.540
and then it drops straight down,

316
00:11:46.540 --> 00:11:48.540
then this condition certainly won't be met

317
00:11:48.540 --> 00:11:49.540
and then it's also not

318
00:11:49.540 --> 00:11:51.540
the right launch site.

319
00:11:51.540 --> 00:11:53.540
Of course, depending on the pilot's skill,

320
00:11:53.540 --> 00:11:55.540
this limit shifts a little.

321
00:11:55.540 --> 00:11:57.540
But this principle applies to everyone

322
00:11:57.540 --> 00:11:58.540
and always.

323
00:11:58.540 --> 00:12:01.250
Then we have, of course,

324
00:12:01.250 --> 00:12:02.250
different criteria

325
00:12:02.250 --> 00:12:03.250
for the launch site.

326
00:12:03.250 --> 00:12:04.250
Meaning, when we arrive,

327
00:12:04.250 --> 00:12:05.250
we first have to know

328
00:12:05.250 --> 00:12:07.250
what kind of wind we have.

329
00:12:07.250 --> 00:12:09.250
If we have a downdraft

330
00:12:09.250 --> 00:12:11.250
i.e. tailwind at the launch site,

331
00:12:11.250 --> 00:12:13.250
then we definitely have to choose a launch site

332
00:12:13.250 --> 00:12:15.250
where we can run for a long way.

333
00:12:15.250 --> 00:12:17.250
Meaning, one that is free of obstacles.

334
00:12:17.250 --> 00:12:19.250
We can't run between stones,

335
00:12:19.250 --> 00:12:20.250
we have to make sure

336
00:12:20.250 --> 00:12:22.250
this section is obstacle-free,

337
00:12:22.250 --> 00:12:23.250
so we can accelerate

338
00:12:23.250 --> 00:12:25.250
and also after lift-off

339
00:12:25.250 --> 00:12:27.250
still need to build speed,

340
00:12:27.250 --> 00:12:29.250
so that it's as obstacle-free and clean as possible.

341
00:12:29.250 --> 00:12:31.250
If we arrive at the launch site

342
00:12:31.250 --> 00:12:33.250
and there's a 20 km/h headwind,

343
00:12:33.250 --> 00:12:35.250
the situation looks of course quite different.

344
00:12:35.250 --> 00:12:37.250
Then we can beautifully

345
00:12:37.250 --> 00:12:38.250
turn around to face the wing

346
00:12:38.250 --> 00:12:40.250
and do a reverse launch.

347
00:12:40.250 --> 00:12:41.250
It can be that

348
00:12:41.250 --> 00:12:42.250
we first have to,

349
00:12:42.250 --> 00:12:44.250
so the wing doesn't overshoot too much,

350
00:12:44.250 --> 00:12:45.250
run toward the wing

351
00:12:45.250 --> 00:12:46.250
up the slope.

352
00:12:46.250 --> 00:12:47.250
That means,

353
00:12:47.250 --> 00:12:48.250
we need to make sure

354
00:12:48.250 --> 00:12:49.550
that we don't have obstacles behind us,

355
00:12:49.550 --> 00:12:51.550
but actually toward the wing,

356
00:12:51.550 --> 00:12:52.550
no obstacles,

357
00:12:52.550 --> 00:12:53.550
so that we don't trip.

358
00:12:53.550 --> 00:12:55.660
The same applies with crosswind.

359
00:12:55.660 --> 00:12:57.660
If we have a bit of crosswind there,

360
00:12:57.660 --> 00:12:58.660
we may need to

361
00:12:58.660 --> 00:12:59.660
pull the wing up against the wind

362
00:12:59.660 --> 00:13:00.660
and then run a small distance

363
00:13:00.660 --> 00:13:02.660
in the fall direction.

364
00:13:02.660 --> 00:13:03.660
Then there must be

365
00:13:03.660 --> 00:13:05.660
as few obstacles as possible.

366
00:13:05.660 --> 00:13:08.000
And that's an important criterion

367
00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:09.000
for the launch site.

368
00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:10.000
That also belongs to

369
00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:12.000
crowd gathering.

370
00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:14.000
Especially at public launch sites

371
00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:16.000
that are reached by lift,

372
00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:18.000
you very quickly get lots of spectators.

373
00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
These spectators are, on one hand, nice

374
00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
because they watch our sport,

375
00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
on the other hand it also poses a danger.

376
00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
Meaning, they may want to talk to you,

377
00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:29.300
they want their questions answered,

378
00:13:29.300 --> 00:13:31.300
and all of that distracts you.

379
00:13:31.300 --> 00:13:33.300
So it may also make sense

380
00:13:33.300 --> 00:13:34.300
to choose a launch site

381
00:13:34.300 --> 00:13:35.300
where you have a bit of peace.

382
00:13:35.300 --> 00:13:36.300
Especially if you're a bit

383
00:13:36.300 --> 00:13:37.300
uncertain,

384
00:13:37.300 --> 00:13:39.300
if you still need to internalise

385
00:13:39.300 --> 00:13:40.300
the whole launch process.

386
00:13:40.300 --> 00:13:42.750
Take your time,

387
00:13:42.750 --> 00:13:43.750
work calmly,

388
00:13:43.750 --> 00:13:44.750
never hectically,

389
00:13:44.750 --> 00:13:52.620
and then there will also be a clean launch.

390
00:13:52.620 --> 00:13:54.620
When you're ready

391
00:13:54.620 --> 00:13:56.640
to start the launch,

392
00:13:56.640 --> 00:13:58.640
one thing is indispensable,

393
00:13:58.640 --> 00:14:00.640
namely that you do a proper check.

394
00:14:00.640 --> 00:14:01.640
And the check,

395
00:14:01.640 --> 00:14:02.640
you've already,

396
00:14:02.640 --> 00:14:03.640
if you've been to the training slope,

397
00:14:03.640 --> 00:14:05.640
certainly learned it there,

398
00:14:05.640 --> 00:14:07.640
is also a very big topic in theory

399
00:14:07.640 --> 00:14:08.780
and it should always

400
00:14:08.780 --> 00:14:10.780
be done conscientiously.

401
00:14:10.780 --> 00:14:12.780
It actually starts

402
00:14:12.780 --> 00:14:14.780
when the harness is on the ground

403
00:14:14.780 --> 00:14:15.780
and you pick it up and put it on,

404
00:14:15.780 --> 00:14:17.780
because then, and only then,

405
00:14:17.780 --> 00:14:18.780
can you properly check

406
00:14:18.780 --> 00:14:22.780
that your reserve handle is sitting cleanly in the harness.

407
00:14:22.780 --> 00:14:23.780
Are the two pins —

408
00:14:23.780 --> 00:14:24.780
most have two,

409
00:14:24.780 --> 00:14:26.780
there are also harnesses with only one —

410
00:14:26.780 --> 00:14:28.780
is the pin really still in,

411
00:14:28.780 --> 00:14:29.780
as it should be,

412
00:14:29.780 --> 00:14:30.780
is the handle properly attached,

413
00:14:30.780 --> 00:14:31.780
does anything look off,

414
00:14:31.780 --> 00:14:33.780
as if something isn't right —

415
00:14:33.780 --> 00:14:34.780
and that's what you can do

416
00:14:34.780 --> 00:14:35.780
when you pick up the harness,

417
00:14:35.780 --> 00:14:37.780
first you check the reserve parachute

418
00:14:37.780 --> 00:14:39.780
and then you put it on.

419
00:14:39.780 --> 00:14:41.780
And then for the 5-point check

420
00:14:41.780 --> 00:14:42.780
the easiest

421
00:14:42.780 --> 00:14:44.780
is to start with the body.

422
00:14:44.780 --> 00:14:46.780
We go from inside to outside.

423
00:14:46.780 --> 00:14:47.860
Namely,

424
00:14:47.860 --> 00:14:49.880
with the reserve parachute already checked,

425
00:14:49.880 --> 00:14:50.880
we then move on

426
00:14:50.880 --> 00:14:52.880
to all our buckles.

427
00:14:52.880 --> 00:14:54.880
Are they closed and secured?

428
00:14:54.880 --> 00:14:56.880
For me, that includes shoelaces,

429
00:14:56.880 --> 00:14:57.880
for me that also includes

430
00:14:57.880 --> 00:14:59.880
the helmet straps.

431
00:14:59.880 --> 00:15:00.880
It's simply important

432
00:15:00.880 --> 00:15:01.880
that all buckles

433
00:15:01.880 --> 00:15:04.500
are closed and secured.

434
00:15:04.500 --> 00:15:05.500
Point 1.

435
00:15:05.500 --> 00:15:06.500
Point 2.

436
00:15:06.500 --> 00:15:07.500
We then go further

437
00:15:07.500 --> 00:15:08.500
from us outward,

438
00:15:08.500 --> 00:15:10.500
namely to the risers.

439
00:15:10.500 --> 00:15:11.500
Are they not twisted?

440
00:15:11.500 --> 00:15:13.500
And do our lines,

441
00:15:13.500 --> 00:15:14.500
going to the wing,

442
00:15:14.500 --> 00:15:15.650
run as we want them to?

443
00:15:15.650 --> 00:15:16.650
That is,

444
00:15:16.650 --> 00:15:17.650
have we sorted them,

445
00:15:17.650 --> 00:15:18.650
is there no knot in there,

446
00:15:18.650 --> 00:15:19.650
do they lie

447
00:15:19.650 --> 00:15:20.650
the way we want?

448
00:15:20.650 --> 00:15:22.650
And then we come to point 3.

449
00:15:22.650 --> 00:15:24.650
Is the wing lying as desired?

450
00:15:24.650 --> 00:15:25.650
Also,

451
00:15:25.650 --> 00:15:26.650
the way we want?

452
00:15:26.650 --> 00:15:27.650
Is it nicely open

453
00:15:27.650 --> 00:15:29.650
and aligned with the wind?

454
00:15:29.650 --> 00:15:30.650
And point 4.

455
00:15:30.650 --> 00:15:32.650
We then move to wind direction

456
00:15:32.650 --> 00:15:33.650
and, important, wind strength.

457
00:15:33.650 --> 00:15:34.650
It's no use

458
00:15:34.650 --> 00:15:36.650
if we have the right wind direction

459
00:15:36.650 --> 00:15:38.650
but a 50 km/h slope updraft

460
00:15:38.650 --> 00:15:40.650
or a 20 km/h tailwind.

461
00:15:40.650 --> 00:15:43.650
Then the strength is certainly not right.

462
00:15:43.650 --> 00:15:46.460
And then point 5.

463
00:15:46.460 --> 00:15:50.510
Are the launch path and airspace clear?

464
00:15:50.510 --> 00:15:53.140
For that, just look up again quickly.

465
00:15:53.140 --> 00:15:54.140
Yes,

466
00:15:54.140 --> 00:15:55.140
there are no

467
00:15:55.140 --> 00:15:56.140
other pilots flying past.

468
00:15:56.140 --> 00:15:58.140
And the launch path

469
00:15:58.140 --> 00:16:00.140
is really clear.

470
00:16:00.140 --> 00:16:01.140
Are there no children

471
00:16:01.140 --> 00:16:02.140
or animals around

472
00:16:02.140 --> 00:16:03.140
that could suddenly

473
00:16:03.140 --> 00:16:05.140
during the launch procedure

474
00:16:05.140 --> 00:16:07.140
walk into your launch path?

475
00:16:07.140 --> 00:16:08.140
If that's the case,

476
00:16:08.140 --> 00:16:09.140
then better wait,

477
00:16:09.140 --> 00:16:11.140
send the children away,

478
00:16:11.140 --> 00:16:12.140
wait

479
00:16:12.140 --> 00:16:14.140
if the cow wants to graze a bit more,

480
00:16:14.140 --> 00:16:16.140
and only then launch.

481
00:16:16.140 --> 00:16:18.140
I can imagine

482
00:16:18.140 --> 00:16:19.140
if you, with your mass,

483
00:16:19.140 --> 00:16:20.140
let's say,

484
00:16:20.140 --> 00:16:21.140
I'm 80 kilos

485
00:16:21.140 --> 00:16:23.140
with the paraglider and everything,

486
00:16:23.140 --> 00:16:24.140
I'm quickly 100 kilos

487
00:16:24.140 --> 00:16:26.140
and I accelerate to 20 km/h,

488
00:16:26.140 --> 00:16:28.140
then that's a kinetic energy

489
00:16:28.140 --> 00:16:29.140
that, for whoever

490
00:16:29.140 --> 00:16:30.140
I might hit,

491
00:16:30.140 --> 00:16:32.140
can very quickly become really dangerous.

492
00:16:32.140 --> 00:16:36.590
If we're doing a reverse launch,

493
00:16:36.590 --> 00:16:37.590
we have good wind,

494
00:16:37.590 --> 00:16:39.590
we can do a perfect reverse launch,

495
00:16:39.590 --> 00:16:42.590
then we turn around after the 5-point check

496
00:16:42.590 --> 00:16:44.800
toward the wing.

497
00:16:44.800 --> 00:16:46.800
Now from points 1 to 4

498
00:16:46.800 --> 00:16:47.800
not much changes anymore,

499
00:16:47.800 --> 00:16:48.800
but what can change again

500
00:16:48.800 --> 00:16:49.800
is,

501
00:16:49.800 --> 00:16:50.800
namely that the launch path

502
00:16:50.800 --> 00:16:51.800
or for example the airspace

503
00:16:51.800 --> 00:16:52.800
is no longer clear.

504
00:16:52.800 --> 00:16:54.800
So immediately before the reverse launch

505
00:16:54.800 --> 00:16:57.800
repeat point 5 carefully again.

506
00:16:57.800 --> 00:17:03.830
Then we slowly proceed to the launch

507
00:17:03.830 --> 00:17:05.830
and you've probably heard of it,

508
00:17:05.830 --> 00:17:08.830
the so-called 3-phase launch.

509
00:17:08.830 --> 00:17:11.830
Namely, we begin with the inflating phase,

510
00:17:11.830 --> 00:17:13.830
then comes the control

511
00:17:13.830 --> 00:17:15.830
and correction phase,

512
00:17:15.830 --> 00:17:17.830
and then comes the acceleration phase.

513
00:17:17.830 --> 00:17:19.830
And it's very important

514
00:17:19.830 --> 00:17:21.830
that we think of it in these three steps.

515
00:17:21.830 --> 00:17:23.830
Many pilots at the launch site

516
00:17:23.830 --> 00:17:25.830
go too far ahead in their minds,

517
00:17:25.830 --> 00:17:26.830
they're already in the air

518
00:17:26.830 --> 00:17:27.830
or already accelerating.

519
00:17:27.830 --> 00:17:28.830
Instead of simply saying:

520
00:17:28.830 --> 00:17:31.830
first I'll do point 1 and point 2 cleanly,

521
00:17:31.830 --> 00:17:32.830
namely inflating,

522
00:17:32.830 --> 00:17:34.830
control and correction,

523
00:17:34.830 --> 00:17:36.830
and then I decide:

524
00:17:36.830 --> 00:17:38.830
everything is the way I want it,

525
00:17:38.830 --> 00:17:39.830
I feel safe,

526
00:17:39.830 --> 00:17:40.830
it feels good,

527
00:17:40.830 --> 00:17:42.830
then I go into the acceleration phase.

528
00:17:42.830 --> 00:17:44.830
And don't do all 3 at once,

529
00:17:44.830 --> 00:17:46.830
because the control and correction phase

530
00:17:46.830 --> 00:17:48.830
is exactly there

531
00:17:48.830 --> 00:17:50.830
so that we recognise a mistake.

532
00:17:50.830 --> 00:17:52.830
The wing is, say, crooked,

533
00:17:52.830 --> 00:17:54.830
we have a knot in the line,

534
00:17:54.830 --> 00:17:57.010
we have something that doesn't suit us —

535
00:17:57.010 --> 00:17:59.010
we abort.

536
00:17:59.010 --> 00:18:01.790
If we're already in the acceleration phase,

537
00:18:01.790 --> 00:18:02.790
we're already there,

538
00:18:02.790 --> 00:18:04.790
an abort can no longer happen,

539
00:18:04.790 --> 00:18:05.790
because as the word says,

540
00:18:05.790 --> 00:18:06.790
acceleration,

541
00:18:06.790 --> 00:18:07.790
we're moving fast

542
00:18:07.790 --> 00:18:08.790
and we want to leave this zone

543
00:18:08.790 --> 00:18:10.790
as quickly as possible,

544
00:18:10.790 --> 00:18:11.790
namely into the air,

545
00:18:11.790 --> 00:18:12.790
because in the air we're safe again.

546
00:18:12.790 --> 00:18:14.790
There we no longer have obstacles to hit,

547
00:18:14.790 --> 00:18:16.790
we can no longer trip,

548
00:18:16.790 --> 00:18:18.810
in the air everything is fine again.

549
00:18:18.810 --> 00:18:19.810
Important is:

550
00:18:19.810 --> 00:18:22.210
do 1 and 2 cleanly

551
00:18:22.210 --> 00:18:23.210
and then decide,

552
00:18:23.210 --> 00:18:25.210
yes, fits, accelerate,

553
00:18:25.210 --> 00:18:26.210
or no, doesn't fit,

554
00:18:26.210 --> 00:18:27.210
abort.

555
00:18:27.210 --> 00:18:30.210
Incidentally, in a practical exam too,

556
00:18:30.210 --> 00:18:33.210
as long as you abort in point 1 or point 2,

557
00:18:33.210 --> 00:18:35.210
that's a clean abort

558
00:18:35.210 --> 00:18:36.210
and no problem.

559
00:18:36.210 --> 00:18:39.210
If you abort in point 3, the acceleration phase,

560
00:18:39.210 --> 00:18:42.210
then you didn't do point 2 cleanly

561
00:18:42.210 --> 00:18:49.000
and that can mean a negative point in the exam.

562
00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:50.000
Important after that,

563
00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.000
when we reach lift-off speed,

564
00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.000
is that we also lift off

565
00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.240
and very importantly,

566
00:18:56.240 --> 00:18:59.240
that you don't release the brakes after launch.

567
00:18:59.240 --> 00:19:01.240
We see it again and again in practice,

568
00:19:01.240 --> 00:19:02.240
that people fly out

569
00:19:02.240 --> 00:19:06.240
and want to get comfortable in the harness relatively quickly.

570
00:19:06.240 --> 00:19:08.240
That's well and good for comfort,

571
00:19:08.240 --> 00:19:10.240
but it carries a risk,

572
00:19:10.240 --> 00:19:12.240
namely that you release the brakes.

573
00:19:12.240 --> 00:19:14.240
And now you have some disturbance

574
00:19:14.240 --> 00:19:15.240
that you maybe didn't even notice during launch

575
00:19:15.240 --> 00:19:17.240
or a bit too much crosswind

576
00:19:17.240 --> 00:19:20.240
and the wing pulls relatively quickly to one side.

577
00:19:20.240 --> 00:19:23.240
And that's simply connected with dangers,

578
00:19:23.240 --> 00:19:26.240
so only sit into the harness then,

579
00:19:26.240 --> 00:19:28.240
only get comfortable then,

580
00:19:28.240 --> 00:19:30.240
when you're flying far, far straight

581
00:19:30.240 --> 00:19:32.240
in the desired flight direction,

582
00:19:32.240 --> 00:19:35.320
have lots of air below you,

583
00:19:35.320 --> 00:19:37.320
then you can release the brakes briefly

584
00:19:37.320 --> 00:19:39.320
and get comfortable

585
00:19:39.320 --> 00:19:41.320
and then take the brakes again.

586
00:19:41.320 --> 00:19:43.320
Now there's also the situation

587
00:19:43.320 --> 00:19:45.320
where you notice immediately after launch

588
00:19:45.320 --> 00:19:47.320
that you're not flying straight

589
00:19:47.320 --> 00:19:49.320
but to the right or to the left.

590
00:19:49.320 --> 00:19:51.320
That can have various causes.

591
00:19:51.320 --> 00:19:52.320
It can, for example, be

592
00:19:52.320 --> 00:19:54.320
that already during launch

593
00:19:54.320 --> 00:19:55.320
we weren't cleanly into the fall line,

594
00:19:55.320 --> 00:19:57.320
but started a bit at an angle.

595
00:19:57.320 --> 00:19:59.320
It can be that we have a knot

596
00:19:59.320 --> 00:20:00.320
that we didn't see

597
00:20:00.320 --> 00:20:02.460
in the line.

598
00:20:02.460 --> 00:20:03.460
Or it can also be

599
00:20:03.460 --> 00:20:04.460
that we have a strong crosswind

600
00:20:04.460 --> 00:20:07.460
pushing us a bit to one side.

601
00:20:07.460 --> 00:20:08.460
Absolutely most important —

602
00:20:08.460 --> 00:20:10.460
and this should actually be the fourth point

603
00:20:10.460 --> 00:20:12.460
in the 3-phase launch.

604
00:20:12.460 --> 00:20:14.540
And the fourth point is actually

605
00:20:14.540 --> 00:20:16.540
the right stabilisation in the

606
00:20:16.540 --> 00:20:17.540
direction we want.

607
00:20:17.540 --> 00:20:19.540
Namely, straight away from the terrain.

608
00:20:19.540 --> 00:20:21.540
And that must be absolute priority,

609
00:20:21.540 --> 00:20:22.540
no matter what the reason is

610
00:20:22.540 --> 00:20:24.540
that we go to one side.

611
00:20:24.540 --> 00:20:26.540
First cleanly shift weight,

612
00:20:26.540 --> 00:20:29.540
efficiently steer with the opposite brake so firmly

613
00:20:29.540 --> 00:20:31.540
that we fly straight,

614
00:20:31.540 --> 00:20:32.540
far, far out,

615
00:20:32.540 --> 00:20:34.540
build distance between us

616
00:20:34.540 --> 00:20:35.540
and the ground

617
00:20:35.540 --> 00:20:42.910
and then take care of the problem.

618
00:20:42.910 --> 00:20:43.910
If we don't do this,

619
00:20:43.910 --> 00:20:45.910
the dangers involved are, I think,

620
00:20:45.910 --> 00:20:46.910
quite obvious.

621
00:20:46.910 --> 00:20:47.910
Namely that we go uncontrolled

622
00:20:47.910 --> 00:20:51.020
back toward the slope.

623
00:20:51.020 --> 00:20:53.020
And depending on the terrain

624
00:20:53.020 --> 00:20:55.140
it's of course not smart

625
00:20:55.140 --> 00:20:57.140
to land in there.

626
00:20:57.140 --> 00:21:00.540
A landing I wouldn't prefer.

627
00:21:00.540 --> 00:21:03.550
I'd always fly out into open airspace,

628
00:21:03.550 --> 00:21:05.550
because then I buy myself time

629
00:21:05.550 --> 00:21:06.550
to react.

630
00:21:06.550 --> 00:21:07.550
And here it's again good —

631
00:21:07.550 --> 00:21:08.550
the bigger my time window,

632
00:21:08.550 --> 00:21:10.550
the more calmly I can tackle the problem

633
00:21:10.550 --> 00:21:14.460
and react accordingly.

634
00:21:14.460 --> 00:21:16.460
Important is, if we have a problem —

635
00:21:16.460 --> 00:21:18.460
let's now take, say,

636
00:21:18.460 --> 00:21:19.460
still a knot in the line,

637
00:21:19.460 --> 00:21:22.460
even though we did our check cleanly.

638
00:21:22.460 --> 00:21:25.460
And we even did the 3-phase launch,

639
00:21:25.460 --> 00:21:26.460
point 2 cleanly done,

640
00:21:26.460 --> 00:21:27.460
namely control and correction,

641
00:21:27.460 --> 00:21:29.460
and stupidly still have

642
00:21:29.460 --> 00:21:30.460
a knot in the line

643
00:21:30.460 --> 00:21:31.460
that we didn't see

644
00:21:31.460 --> 00:21:33.460
and we're now flying out.

645
00:21:33.460 --> 00:21:35.460
Important is: stabilise,

646
00:21:35.460 --> 00:21:36.480
fly straight,

647
00:21:36.480 --> 00:21:38.480
as already discussed.

648
00:21:38.480 --> 00:21:40.530
And speaking of knots,

649
00:21:40.530 --> 00:21:42.580
in their whole flying career

650
00:21:42.580 --> 00:21:44.580
there's probably no pilot

651
00:21:44.580 --> 00:21:46.660
who says they've never had a knot.

652
00:21:46.660 --> 00:21:47.660
Or rather, ever had one.

653
00:21:47.660 --> 00:21:48.660
It's something

654
00:21:48.660 --> 00:21:50.660
that you simply go through,

655
00:21:50.660 --> 00:21:52.660
because we have loose lines

656
00:21:52.660 --> 00:21:54.660
and usually in rocky places,

657
00:21:54.660 --> 00:21:55.660
where you might have pebbles

658
00:21:55.660 --> 00:21:56.660
or tall grass,

659
00:21:56.660 --> 00:21:58.660
where a knot can form.

660
00:21:58.660 --> 00:22:00.660
It's not tragic,

661
00:22:00.660 --> 00:22:01.660
as long as you know

662
00:22:01.660 --> 00:22:02.660
how to deal with it.

663
00:22:02.660 --> 00:22:03.660
Important is,

664
00:22:03.660 --> 00:22:04.660
when we have it,

665
00:22:04.660 --> 00:22:05.860
fly out,

666
00:22:05.860 --> 00:22:06.860
open airspace,

667
00:22:06.860 --> 00:22:07.860
now I take care of the problem

668
00:22:07.860 --> 00:22:09.860
and now I first look

669
00:22:09.860 --> 00:22:10.860
at what the problem is.

670
00:22:10.860 --> 00:22:11.860
Do I recognise,

671
00:22:11.860 --> 00:22:12.860
aha,

672
00:22:12.860 --> 00:22:14.860
I really do have a knot now.

673
00:22:14.860 --> 00:22:17.070
If I have this knot,

674
00:22:17.070 --> 00:22:19.660
then I can decide,

675
00:22:19.660 --> 00:22:21.660
do I get this knot to open?

676
00:22:21.660 --> 00:22:23.660
There are various tools

677
00:22:23.660 --> 00:22:24.660
for opening the knot.

678
00:22:24.660 --> 00:22:25.660
That can, for example, be

679
00:22:25.660 --> 00:22:27.660
that I give an impulse with the brake

680
00:22:27.660 --> 00:22:29.660
on the knot side.

681
00:22:29.660 --> 00:22:30.660
It can be

682
00:22:30.660 --> 00:22:32.660
that the knot opens again.

683
00:22:32.660 --> 00:22:33.660
It can be

684
00:22:33.660 --> 00:22:34.660
that I pull on the stabilo line,

685
00:22:34.660 --> 00:22:35.660
that's the outermost colour,

686
00:22:35.660 --> 00:22:37.660
usually the trim line,

687
00:22:37.660 --> 00:22:39.660
that goes to the stabilo,

688
00:22:39.660 --> 00:22:41.660
that I pull this down.

689
00:22:41.660 --> 00:22:43.660
Or I have a knot, for example,

690
00:22:43.660 --> 00:22:45.660
that's at the front,

691
00:22:45.660 --> 00:22:46.660
with a collapse,

692
00:22:46.660 --> 00:22:48.660
a 50% collapse,

693
00:22:48.660 --> 00:22:50.660
which we'll come back to later,

694
00:22:50.660 --> 00:22:51.660
how that's done,

695
00:22:51.660 --> 00:22:53.660
I can unload the wing in such a way

696
00:22:53.660 --> 00:22:54.660
that there's a good chance

697
00:22:54.660 --> 00:22:55.660
that the knot opens again.

698
00:22:55.660 --> 00:22:57.260
When the knot opens,

699
00:22:57.260 --> 00:22:58.260
great,

700
00:22:58.260 --> 00:22:59.260
then we fly on,

701
00:22:59.260 --> 00:23:00.260
enjoy this flight.

702
00:23:00.260 --> 00:23:02.260
If the knot doesn't open.

703
00:23:02.260 --> 00:23:03.260
And we can hold the state

704
00:23:03.260 --> 00:23:04.260
of flying straight

705
00:23:04.260 --> 00:23:05.260
for the time being,

706
00:23:05.260 --> 00:23:07.260
by shifting weight firmly,

707
00:23:07.260 --> 00:23:09.260
applying a bit of opposite brake,

708
00:23:09.260 --> 00:23:10.260
and flying straight.

709
00:23:10.260 --> 00:23:11.260
Then we have to decide,

710
00:23:11.260 --> 00:23:13.260
can we land like this?

711
00:23:13.260 --> 00:23:15.260
And if we can answer this question

712
00:23:15.260 --> 00:23:16.260
with 100%,

713
00:23:16.260 --> 00:23:17.260
answer it,

714
00:23:17.260 --> 00:23:18.260
then we do it.

715
00:23:18.260 --> 00:23:20.270
Then we land like this.

716
00:23:20.270 --> 00:23:22.270
But if we're uncertain

717
00:23:22.270 --> 00:23:23.270
and say,

718
00:23:23.270 --> 00:23:24.270
flying straight,

719
00:23:24.270 --> 00:23:25.270
fine, that works,

720
00:23:25.270 --> 00:23:26.270
but now for landing

721
00:23:26.270 --> 00:23:27.270
I'd also have to do turns

722
00:23:27.270 --> 00:23:28.270
and also turn into the wind

723
00:23:28.270 --> 00:23:29.270
and I don't even know

724
00:23:29.270 --> 00:23:30.270
where the landing site is,

725
00:23:30.270 --> 00:23:31.270
then we'll quickly

726
00:23:31.270 --> 00:23:32.270
become overloaded.

727
00:23:32.270 --> 00:23:33.270
Then it makes absolute sense,

728
00:23:33.270 --> 00:23:34.270
as long as we can still steer,

729
00:23:34.270 --> 00:23:35.270
over a large field,

730
00:23:35.270 --> 00:23:37.270
preferably not over woods,

731
00:23:37.270 --> 00:23:38.270
to fly over a large meadow

732
00:23:38.270 --> 00:23:40.270
and then deploy the reserve parachute.

733
00:23:40.270 --> 00:23:41.290
Reserve parachute situations

734
00:23:41.290 --> 00:23:43.290
we'll come back to later,

735
00:23:43.290 --> 00:23:45.290
but at least you've heard about it once.

736
00:23:46.290 --> 00:23:47.780
The dog-leg curve.

737
00:23:47.780 --> 00:23:49.780
The dog-leg curve is actually what

738
00:23:49.780 --> 00:23:50.780
we want to avoid,

739
00:23:50.780 --> 00:23:51.780
because it ultimately

740
00:23:51.780 --> 00:23:52.780
costs us flight path

741
00:23:52.780 --> 00:23:53.780
and time,

742
00:23:53.780 --> 00:23:54.780
meaning

743
00:23:54.780 --> 00:23:55.780
we arrive at lower altitude

744
00:23:55.780 --> 00:23:56.780
at the point

745
00:23:56.780 --> 00:23:57.780
where we want to.

746
00:23:57.780 --> 00:23:59.780
If we now aim at a point

747
00:23:59.780 --> 00:24:00.780
and we have no wind,

748
00:24:00.780 --> 00:24:01.780
then we just fly toward it

749
00:24:01.780 --> 00:24:03.780
and arrive as nicely high

750
00:24:03.780 --> 00:24:04.780
as we want.

751
00:24:04.780 --> 00:24:05.780
If we now, however,

752
00:24:05.780 --> 00:24:06.780
have a crosswind component,

753
00:24:06.780 --> 00:24:08.780
in this case from the left,

754
00:24:08.780 --> 00:24:09.780
and we simply

755
00:24:09.780 --> 00:24:10.780
fly toward the point,

756
00:24:10.780 --> 00:24:11.780
then there's a so-called

757
00:24:11.780 --> 00:24:12.780
dog-leg curve

758
00:24:12.780 --> 00:24:13.780
and we make,

759
00:24:13.780 --> 00:24:14.780
exaggerated,

760
00:24:14.780 --> 00:24:15.780
a large detour

761
00:24:15.780 --> 00:24:16.780
and arrive noticeably

762
00:24:16.780 --> 00:24:17.780
lower at the point

763
00:24:17.780 --> 00:24:18.780
than maybe we want.

764
00:24:18.780 --> 00:24:19.780
That's why we have to

765
00:24:19.780 --> 00:24:20.780
choose a wind-correction angle.

766
00:24:20.780 --> 00:24:22.780
The wind-correction angle is nothing other than

767
00:24:22.780 --> 00:24:23.780
the angle between

768
00:24:23.780 --> 00:24:24.780
the longitudinal axis of the wing

769
00:24:24.780 --> 00:24:25.780
and the flight path

770
00:24:25.780 --> 00:24:26.780
we choose.

771
00:24:26.780 --> 00:24:29.340
And if we choose this

772
00:24:29.340 --> 00:24:31.340
a bit into the wind,

773
00:24:31.340 --> 00:24:33.340
then we make a nice,

774
00:24:33.340 --> 00:24:34.340
straight line

775
00:24:34.340 --> 00:24:35.340
toward the point

776
00:24:35.340 --> 00:24:36.340
and arrive optimally

777
00:24:36.340 --> 00:24:37.340
where we want.

778
00:24:37.340 --> 00:24:38.340
to be.
